# Patterns Reference Content

Greek-specific sentence constructions that work differently than English.

## Purpose

Explain grammar patterns that don't map directly to English. These constructions require understanding the Greek way of thinking.

## Key Insight

Some Greek constructions work differently than English. Learn these patterns and you'll understand why "I like coffee" becomes "Coffee pleases me."

---

## Likes Construction (μου αρέσει / αρέσουν)

<pattern name="likes-construction" color="ocean">
<title>Likes Construction</title>
<subtitle>μου αρέσει / αρέσουν</subtitle>

<principle>
[Person] αρέσει (one thing) / αρέσουν (many things)
The thing liked is the SUBJECT!
</principle>

### One thing (αρέσει)
| Greek              | English           |
|--------------------|-------------------|
| Μου αρέσει         | I like (it)       |
| Σου αρέσει         | You like (it)     |
| Του/Της αρέσει     | He/She likes (it) |
| Μας αρέσει         | We like (it)      |
| Σας αρέσει         | You (pl.) like (it)|
| Τους αρέσει        | They like (it)    |

### Many things (αρέσουν)
| Greek              | English            |
|--------------------|--------------------|
| Μου αρέσουν        | I like (them)      |
| Σου αρέσουν        | You like (them)    |
| Του/Της αρέσουν    | He/She likes (them)|
| Μας αρέσουν        | We like (them)     |
| Σας αρέσουν        | You (pl.) like (them)|
| Τους αρέσουν       | They like (them)   |

</pattern>

---

## Quick Test: αρέσει or αρέσουν?

<decision-guide name="likes-test">
<intro>Choose the correct verb form based on what is liked.</intro>

### One thing is liked (singular subject) → αρέσει
| Greek                   | English               |
|-------------------------|-----------------------|
| Μου αρέσει ο καφές      | I like coffee         |
| Σου αρέσει η μουσική;   | Do you like the music?|

### Multiple things are liked (plural subject) → αρέσουν
| Greek                   | English               |
|-------------------------|-----------------------|
| Μου αρέσουν οι γάτες    | I like cats           |
| Τους αρέσουν τα βιβλία  | They like books       |

<summary>
Remember: the thing liked is the **subject**, so the verb agrees with it!
</summary>

</decision-guide>

